FIG. 2 is a schematic illustration of the electrode pad of the prior art tool of FIG. 1;


FIG. 3 is a schematic illustration of an electrode pad of an imaging tool according to the invention;


FIG. 4a is a part schematic and part block diagram of an imaging tool according to the invention;


FIG. 4b is a schematic illustration of vertical current flow parallel to the electrode pad of the invention;


FIG. 5 is a graph showing five plots of current against depth in a conductive bed covered with resistive mudcakes of different resistivity, the current measurements having been made with a prior art FMI (tm)  tool;


FIG. 6 is a graph similar to FIG. 5 where the measurements have been taken in a resistive bed;


FIG. 7 is a graph showing five plots of voltage against depth in a conductive bed covered with resistive mudcakes of different resistivity, the voltage measurements having been made with a tool according to the invention;


FIG. 8 is a graph similar to FIG. 7 where the measurements have been taken in a resistive bed;


FIG. 9 is a schematic illustration of an alternate, less preferred, embodiment of the invention with current flow properly aligned orthogonal to bed boundaries;


FIG. 10 is a schematic illustration of the embodiment of FIG. 9 where current flow is tangential to bed boundaries;


FIG. 11 is a schematic illustration of the more preferred embodiment (also illustrated in FIG. 3) with current flow in two dimensions;


FIG. 12 is a view similar to FIG. 11 of a presently most preferred embodiment of the invention having an optimized electrode arrangement; and


FIG. 13 is a schematic illustration of a matrix of voltage sampling points used to form a resistivity image according to the invention.
